DATA = {
    "25": {
        "1": "<p><strong>ben-esrîm vĕhamēš šānāh ʾămazĕyāhû bemolkô</strong> — 'Amaziah was 25 years old when he became king.' <em>ʾĂmazĕyāhû</em> (H568 — 'YHWH is strong/mighty') begins a nuanced reign. The Chronicler's opening formula (<em>wayyaʿas hayyāšār beʿênê YHWH</em> — 'he did what was right in YHWH's eyes') is immediately qualified by <em>welōʾ belēḇāḇ šālēm</em> — 'but not with a whole heart.' The contrast between formal compliance and inner commitment is the Chronicler's key evaluative category throughout: external right-doing without the <em>lēḇāḇ šālēm</em> (whole heart) cannot sustain covenant faithfulness. Amaziah's reign will illustrate exactly this pattern — partial obedience preceding catastrophic pride.</p>",
        "2": "<p><strong>vayyehi kaʾăšer ḥāzeqāh hammamlākhāh ʿālāyw</strong> — 'When the kingdom was established under him.' <em>Ḥāzeq</em> (H2388 — to be strong, to seize, establish) marks the moment when royal power was sufficiently consolidated to act. The execution of his father's assassins (<em>hamĕsākĕkîm ʾet-ʾāḇîhū</em>) without harming their children is explicitly grounded in the Torah (<em>kakkāṯûḇ bĕṯôrat mōšeh</em>) — specifically Deut 24:16, 'Fathers shall not die for children, children shall not die for fathers.' The Chronicler presents this as Amaziah's first act of piety: applying the covenant law where ancient custom might have demanded clan vengeance.</p>",
        "3": "<p><strong>welōʾ hēmît ʾet-benêhem kî kakatuv bĕtôrat mōšeh</strong> — 'He did not put their children to death, as written in the Torah of Moses.' The direct citation of Torah (<em>ḇĕtôrat mōšeh ʾăšer-tsiwwāh YHWH lēʾmōr</em>) is significant: Amaziah's restraint was not political prudence but covenantal compliance. In the ancient Near East, the sons of regicides were routinely executed to eliminate future vendetta threats (cf. the Jehu dynasty's elimination of Ahab's 70 sons). The Chronicler's note establishes Amaziah as initially Torah-obedient — the foil that makes his subsequent idolatry so tragic. The king who cited Torah in mercy will later worship the gods of the people he conquered.</p>",
        "5": "<p><strong>vayyiqbbōts ʾămazĕyāhû ʾet-yehûdāh</strong> — 'Amaziah mustered Judah.' The military census counted <em>shloshah meʾôt ʾelef bāḥûr</em> (300,000 choice young men) from Judah and Benjamin — notably the Levites were exempt from military conscription (cf. Num 1:49). The age minimum was <em>miben-esrîm šānāh</em> (20 years) — the same Mosaic census threshold (Num 1:3). The force was armed with <em>romah wātsinnāh</em> (spear and shield), the standard heavy infantry equipment of the 8th century BCE Levantine armies as confirmed by Assyrian relief carvings.</p>",
        "6": "<p><strong>vayyiśkōr miśśĕrāʾēl meʾāh ʾelef gibbôr ḥayil</strong> — 'He hired from Israel 100,000 mighty warriors.' The <em>meʾāh ʾelef gibbôr ḥayil</em> (100,000 mighty warriors) hired for <em>meʾāh kikkar kesep</em> (100 talents of silver) represented a major financial outlay and a diplomatic transaction with the northern kingdom. The use of <em>gibbôr ḥayil</em> (mighty warrior — H1368, H2428 — the same designation for Boaz, David's champions) for Israelite mercenaries is neutral in itself, but their engagement with a king condemned for his divided heart already sets up the coming prophetic intervention.</p>",
        "7": "<p><strong>weʾîš hāʾĕlōhîm bāʾ ʾēlāyw lēʾmōr</strong> — 'A man of God came to him saying.' The anonymous prophet (<em>ʾîš hāʾĕlōhîm</em>) delivers the theological key to the story: <em>YHWH ʾên ʿim-yisrāʾel kōl bĕnê ʾeprayim</em> — 'YHWH is not with Israel, all the sons of Ephraim.' The northern kingdom under its Baal-worship kings no longer enjoyed YHWH's military backing. To bring Israelite troops into Judah's army would contaminate the campaign with YHWH-opposed personnel. The theological principle: military power without YHWH's presence is not just neutral but actively dangerous — it transfers the opponent's spiritual condition onto Judah's war.</p>",
        "8": "<p><strong>veʾim-bāʾ ʿăśēh chăzeq lammilḥāmāh</strong> — 'If you go and are strong for the battle.' The conditional construction reflects the free-will dimension: Amaziah could disobey. The prophet's argument is economic-theological: <em>yêš kōaḥ lēʾlōhîm laʿăzôr ûlehakšîl</em> — 'God has power to help and to cause stumbling.' YHWH is the decisive variable in battle, not the size of the force. The loss of 100 talents of silver is recoverable; the loss of YHWH's favor is not. The prophet frames this as a test of Amaziah's trust: will he bank on human numbers or on divine power?</p>",
        "9": "<p><strong>vayyōʾmer ʾămazĕyāhû leʾîš hāʾĕlōhîm</strong> — 'Amaziah said to the man of God.' Amaziah's practical question — <em>ûmāh-laʿăśôt lĕmeʾāh hakkikkar ʾăšer nātattî legedûd yisrāʾel</em> ('what shall I do about the 100 talents I gave to the Israelite division?') — reveals a partially compliant heart. He accepts the theological argument but frets about the financial loss. The prophet's response models kingdom economics: <em>yeš laYHWH lātet lekhā harbēh mizzeh</em> — 'YHWH is able to give you much more than this.' Covenant faithfulness yields more than any mercenary contract. Amaziah complies — for now.</p>",
        "10": "<p><strong>vayyabdîlēm ʾămazĕyāhû laggĕdûd ʾăšer-bāʾ ʾēlāyw mēʾeprayim</strong> — 'Amaziah dismissed the division that had come to him from Ephraim.' The dismissal produced <em>חֲרִי-אַף גָּדוֹל</em> (<em>ḥărî-ʾap gādôl</em> — fierce anger) in the Israelite troops. Being discharged without combat meant no plunder, no honor, and the journey home empty-handed. Their anger was not merely wounded pride but economic grievance: mercenary soldiers expected payment through battle spoils. Their departure precedes an act of revenge (v13) — they raid Judean cities on the way home, killing 3,000. Amaziah's obedience to YHWH paradoxically triggered a secondary crisis.</p>",
        "11": "<p><strong>wayyitḥazzēq ʾămazĕyāhû vayyōlīkh ʾet-ʿammô</strong> — 'Amaziah took courage and led his people.' The verb <em>hitḥazzēq</em> (H2388 — to strengthen oneself, take courage) appears frequently in Chronicles as the act of steeling oneself for a divinely sanctioned undertaking (cf. David to Solomon, 1 Chr 22:13). The Edomite campaign: Amaziah led his forces to Gei-hamelach (<em>gêʾ hammelaḥ</em> — the Valley of Salt, probably near Beer-sheba), killed 10,000 Edomites (<em>ʾelep benê-seir</em>) in battle. The Valley of Salt was also the site of David's victory over Edom (1 Chr 18:12), creating a dynastic parallel.</p>",
        "12": "<p><strong>ûʿăśeret ʾălāfîm ḥāyîm šāḇû benê yehûdāh</strong> — '10,000 alive the men of Judah captured.' The fate of the 10,000 Edomite prisoners is extraordinary: they were taken to a cliff summit (<em>lerōʾš hassela</em> — to the top of the rock/Sela) and thrown off (<em>yišlîkhûm mîrōʾš hassela vikulām nifleqû</em> — 'they cast them from the top of the rock and all of them were split open'). The word <em>sela</em> (H5553 — rock, cliff) is the same word for the Edomite capital Petra (<em>Sela</em>). This atrocity — mass execution by precipice — goes unremarked by the Chronicler but stands in the narrative as foreshadowing: Amaziah himself will fall from height (politically) for the very same pride that led to such excess.</p>",
        "13": "<p><strong>ûbenê haggĕdûd ʾăšer-hēšîb ʾămazĕyāhû</strong> — 'The men of the division that Amaziah sent back.' The discharged Israelite mercenaries — nursing their wounded pride — raided Judean cities from Samaria to Beth-horon, killing 3,000 and taking great plunder (<em>bizzāh rabbāh</em>). The place-names locate the raids in the central hill country between Israel and Judah. This sub-plot demonstrates the law of unintended consequences in covenant narrative: obedience to YHWH (dismissing the mercenaries) created a new problem. But the Chronicler's point is that Amaziah should have trusted YHWH to manage the fallout — as He was managing it, preparing an even greater victory at Sela.</p>",
        "14": "<p><strong>vayhî ʾaḥărê bôʾ ʾămazĕyāhû mehaKot ʾet-ʾedôm</strong> — 'After Amaziah returned from striking Edom.' The theological pivot of ch25: after YHWH's victory over Edom, Amaziah brought back the gods of the Edomites (<em>welōhê benê-seir hēḇîʾ</em>) and set them up as his own gods (<em>leʾlōhîm lô vayyishtaḥû lefānêhem</em> — 'as gods for himself and worshiped before them'). The utter irrationality of worshiping the gods of a conquered people — gods demonstrably unable to defend their own devotees — is precisely the Chronicler's ironic point. YHWH gave Amaziah victory over Edom; Amaziah responded by adopting Edom's helpless gods. This is the <em>šûḇ</em> away from YHWH that will lead to his ruin.</p>",
        "17": "<p><strong>wayyiiwwāʿats ʾămazĕyāhû melek-yehûdāh</strong> — 'Amaziah king of Judah took counsel.' Emboldened by his Edomite victory — and now spiritually compromised by Edomite idolatry — Amaziah challenged Jehoash (<em>Yōʾāš</em>) king of Israel to open battle. The Chronicler notes the pride beneath the challenge: <em>lēk nitrāʾeh fānîm</em> ('come, let us look each other in the face' — a challenge to combat). Amaziah's military confidence after Edom had inflated beyond his actual capacity. Pride (<em>geʾāwāh</em>) here functions as the mechanism by which YHWH's judgment arrives — Amaziah's idolatry led to pride, and pride led to the battle that would break him.</p>",
        "18": "<p><strong>vayyišlaḥ yōʾāš melek-yisrāʾel ʾel-ʾămazĕyāhû</strong> — 'Jehoash king of Israel sent to Amaziah.' The parable of the thistle (<em>ḥōaḥ halleḇānôn</em> — the thornbush of Lebanon) and the cedar (<em>ʾerez ʾăšer balleḇānôn</em>): a wild animal passed by and trampled the thistle. The comparison is devastating — Amaziah is the self-important thistle seeking alliance with the cedar, only to be trampled by the first passing beast. Jehoash's counter-advice: <em>šeḇ beḇêtekhā lāmāh titrāggāz berāʿāh</em> — 'stay home, why provoke trouble and fall — you and Judah with you?' The military pragmatist sees what Amaziah cannot: overreach based on a limited victory invites catastrophe.</p>",
        "19": "<p><strong>ʾāmartā hinnēh hikkîtā ʾet-ʾedôm ûnĕśāʾăkhā libbĕkhā</strong> — 'You say, “I have struck Edom,” and your heart lifted up.' Jehoash diagnoses Amaziah's condition with surgical precision: <em>nĕśāʾ libbĕkhā</em> (your heart is lifted up — pride). The same verb (<em>nāśāʾ lēḇ</em>) describes Uzziah's pride in ch26:16 — the Chronicler traces a pattern. The theological danger: <em>higgāhēr bekhā</em> (boast in your house). The pride born of military success, amplified by idolatry, now drives Amaziah toward a confrontation he cannot win. YHWH's sovereign judgment operates through Amaziah's own delusion — a king bent on self-destruction cannot hear wise counsel.</p>",
        "20": "<p><strong>welōʾ-šāmaʿ ʾămazĕyāhû kî meʾēt hāʾĕlōhîm hîʾ</strong> — 'Amaziah did not listen, for it was from God.' The theological explanation for Amaziah's fatal stubbornness: <em>meʾēt hāʾĕlōhîm hîʾ lemaʿan têt ʾôtām beyad ʾōyĕḇêhem</em> — 'it was from God, in order to deliver them into the hand of their enemies.' This is the Chronicler's theology of judicial hardening: YHWH uses the consequences of a nation's own sin as the instrument of judgment. Amaziah's idolatry (v14) had already sealed the verdict; his pride and deaf ear to counsel were the psychological mechanisms through which the judgment arrived. He sought the gods of those he conquered and was then conquered himself.</p>",
        "21": "<p><strong>vayyaʿal yōʾāš melek-yisrāʾel vayyitrāʾû hûʾ veʾămazĕyāhû</strong> — 'Jehoash king of Israel went up; they faced each other.' The battle location — <em>bêt-šemeš ʾăšer lîhûdāh</em> (Beth-shemesh in Judah, an important border city) — is approximately 25 km west of Jerusalem. Judah was routed (<em>vayyinnāgep yehûdāh lifnê yisrāʾel</em> — Judah was struck before Israel). The humiliation: a southern army retreating toward its own capital, pursued by its northern neighbor. The irony is complete — Amaziah defeated 10,000 Edomites and then fled from fellow Israelites. YHWH's judgment matched the sin exactly: the king who adopted Edom's gods was beaten by a people among whom YHWH was no longer present.</p>",
        "22": "<p><strong>vayyinnāgep yehûdāh lifnê yisrāʾel vayyānusû</strong> — 'Judah was struck before Israel and fled.' The rout was complete: <em>wayyānusû ʾîš leʾohālāyw</em> (each man fled to his tent — an idiom for complete dissolution of an army). The capture of Amaziah himself at Beth-shemesh completes the humiliation. A king who challenged another king to 'look each other in the face' (<em>nitrāʾeh fānîm</em>) now faces his conqueror as a prisoner of war. The linguistic irony of <em>rāʾāh fānîm</em> is complete: Amaziah wanted to face Jehoash in combat; he now faces him as a captive.</p>",
        "23": "<p><strong>veʾet-ʾămazĕyāhû melek-yehûdāh ben-yōʾāš ben-yĕhôʾāḥāz</strong> — 'Amaziah king of Judah, son of Joash son of Jehoahaz.' The genealogical precision in Jehoash's account of his captive is a form of contempt — naming Amaziah by his full paternal lineage while holding him prisoner. The walls of Jerusalem were breached: <em>vayiphrots bĕḥômat yĕrûšālaim</em> (he broke down the wall of Jerusalem) from the Ephraim Gate (<em>šaʿar ʾeprayim</em>) to the Corner Gate (<em>šaʿar hapinnāh</em>) — a stretch of 400 cubits. The northern boundary of Jerusalem's wall was dismantled, leaving the city defenseless. The temple and palace treasuries were looted, and hostages were taken.</p>",
        "24": "<p><strong>weʾēt kol-hazzāhāḇ vehaKesep weʾēt kol-hakkēlîm</strong> — 'all the gold and silver and all the vessels.' The double plunder of the sacred and the royal: <em>bêt hāʾĕlōhîm ʿim ʿōḇēd ʾedôm</em> (the house of God with Obed-edom — the temple treasury-keeper introduced in 1 Chr 26:4-8) and <em>ôtsrôt bêt hammelekh</em> (the palace treasuries). The temple that Solomon had filled with silver and gold (ch5) was now being stripped by an Israelite king. The Chronicler's bitter irony: Amaziah worshiped Edomite gods and the temple of YHWH was stripped — cause and consequence aligned. The mention of <em>ʾōḇēd ʾedôm</em> is a detail only the Chronicler preserves.</p>",
        "25": "<p><strong>vayyiḥyeh ʾămazĕyāhû ben-yōʾāš melek-yehûdāh</strong> — 'Amaziah son of Joash king of Judah lived.' Amaziah survived Jehoash by 15 years — an anticlimatic detail highlighting the long aftermath of his catastrophic failure. The note that he survived Jehoash (<em>ʾaḥărê môt yōʾāš ben-yĕhôʾāḥāz melek yisrāʾel ḥămîšĕ ʿeśrēh šānāh</em>) is a historian's synchronism, anchoring the Judean and Israelite timelines. But Amaziah's reign ended in conspiracy — he fled to Lachish from a plot against him in Jerusalem and was killed there, then brought back to Jerusalem for burial.</p>",
        "26": "<p><strong>weyeter diḇrê ʾămazĕyāhû hārīšonîm vehaʾăḥarōnîm</strong> — 'The rest of the acts of Amaziah, first and last.' The source reference formula — <em>hălōʾ hinnām ketûḇîm ʿal-sefer malkhê yehûdāh veyisrāʾel</em> — points to the now-lost royal annals. The Chronicler's abridged version has selected the theologically significant events: the Torah-obedience at the start, the Edomite victory, the fatal idolatry, the prophetic confrontation, the defeat by Jehoash, and the conspiracy. The pattern is clear: partial obedience → military blessing → pride → idolatry → humiliation → conspiracy. Amaziah is a cautionary example of a half-hearted covenant relationship.</p>",
        "27": "<p><strong>vayyiqqošrû ʿālāyw qešer bîrûšālāim vayyānos lākîš</strong> — 'They conspired against him in Jerusalem and he fled to Lachish.' The conspiracy (<em>qešer</em> — H7195, the same word for the plots that killed his father and grandfather) caught up with Amaziah. He fled to <em>Lākîš</em> (Lachish — 40 km SW of Jerusalem, the second most important city in Judah, later the subject of Sennacherib's famous siege reliefs). His killers pursued him there, suggesting the conspiracy had broad support. His body was returned to Jerusalem on horseback (<em>basûsîm</em>) and buried in the City of David. The dignity of burial in the royal city partially redeems his inglorious end.</p>",
        "28": "<p><strong>vayyimlōkh ʿuzziyyāhû bĕnô taḥtāyw</strong> — 'His son Uzziah reigned in his place.' Uzziah's accession at age 16 (<em>ben-šeš ʿeśrēh šānāh</em>) begins a 52-year reign — the longest in Judah's history outside of Manasseh. The closing verse links the Amaziah narrative to its sequel: the father's failure became the background against which the son's remarkable success would stand in contrast. The Chronicler uses the transition verse to signal a genuine dynastic continuity — despite Amaziah's catastrophe, the Davidic line remained unbroken and would produce in Uzziah one of Judah's most capable kings.</p>",
    },
    "26": {
        "1": "<p><strong>vayyiqqĕḥû kol-ʿam yehûdāh ʾet-ʿuzziyyāhû</strong> — 'All the people of Judah took Uzziah.' <em>ʿUzziyyāhû</em> (H5818 — 'YHWH is my strength') is also called <em>ʾAzaryāhû</em> (YHWH has helped) in 2 Kgs 14:21. The dual name may reflect a throne name and personal name distinction. The phrase <em>vayyiqqĕḥû kol-ʿam yehûdāh</em> (all the people of Judah took him) indicates popular acclamation — the people chose Uzziah rather than waiting for formal succession protocol. At 16 years old, taking the throne after his father's humiliating death, Uzziah's long reign would bring Judah back to a position of power not seen since Solomon.</p>",
        "2": "<p><strong>hûʾ bānāh ʾet-ʾêlôt vayyĕšîḇehā lîhûdāh</strong> — 'He built Elath and restored it to Judah.' <em>ʾÊlôt</em> (Elath/Eilat — H359, the port city at the head of the Gulf of Aqaba) had been under Judean control under Solomon but lost. Its restoration gave Judah access to the Red Sea trade routes — Arabia, East Africa, and India. The Chronicler notes this accomplishment in Uzziah's first verse because it signals the economic dimension of his reign: Judah regained strategic seaport access that would underpin regional commerce. <em>ʾAḥărê šĕḵaḇ hammelekh</em> ('after the king lay down' — i.e., after Amaziah's death) establishes the timing as immediate upon accession.</p>",
        "3": "<p><strong>ben-šeš ʿeśrēh šānāh ʿuzziyyāhû bemalekô</strong> — 'Uzziah was 16 years old when he became king.' The fifty-two year reign (<em>ḥămiššîm ûštayim šānāh mālaḵ bîrûšālāim</em>) spans approximately 792-740 BCE — one of the longest in Judean history. His mother's name <em>Yĕkolĕyāhû</em> (YHWH enables me — H3203) is the Chronicler's practice of recording royal mothers, emphasizing the covenant community's matrilineal heritage alongside the patrilineal royal succession. Jerusalem's prominence during this reign was remarkable; the prophet Isaiah's inaugural vision came in 'the year that King Uzziah died' (Isa 6:1), suggesting his death marked a major era transition.</p>",
        "4": "<p><strong>vayyaʿas hayyāšār beʿênê YHWH kekōl ʾăšer-ʿāśāh ʾămazĕyāhû ʾāḇîhū</strong> — 'He did what was right in YHWH's eyes, just as Amaziah his father had done.' The comparison to Amaziah is deliberately partial — Amaziah did right 'but not with a whole heart.' Uzziah's reign will show an initial period of genuine covenant faithfulness that eventually collapsed under pride. The Chronicler's structural parallel is intentional: both father and son began well and ended badly, but Uzziah's good period was longer and more substantial, his failure more spectacular. The dynastic pattern of starting well and finishing poorly haunts the Davidic line.</p>",
        "6": "<p><strong>vayyētsēʾ vayyilāḥem baplishtîm vayyiphrōts beḥômat gat</strong> — 'He went out and fought against the Philistines and broke down the wall of Gath.' The military campaigns: Uzziah dismantled the fortifications of <em>Gat</em> (Gath), <em>Yavneh</em> (Jabneh), and <em>ʾAšdôd</em> (Ashdod) — three of the Philistine pentapolis cities. The phrase <em>vayyiphrōts beḥômat</em> (he broke through the wall of) uses the same verb as Jehoash's breach of Jerusalem's wall (25:23) — the Chronicler creates a deliberate reversal: where Jerusalem was breached by Israel, Uzziah now breaches Philistine cities. He also built cities (<em>yiḇneh ûḇeʾašdôd</em>) among the Philistines, establishing Judean military presence in their territory.</p>",
        "7": "<p><strong>vayyaʿzŏr-lô hāʾĕlōhîm ʿal-pĕlishtîm</strong> — 'God helped him against the Philistines.' The divine assistance formula (<em>ʾĕlōhîm ʿāzar</em>) recurs throughout the Chronicler's positive military reports (cf. 1 Chr 12:18; 2 Chr 14:11; 18:31). The coalition of enemies defeated: <em>pĕlishtîm, ʿăraḇîm ûbĕgûr baʿal, hammĕʿûnîm</em> (Philistines, Arabs at Gur-baal, the Meunites — a tribal group from Edom/Sinai). The Meunites (<em>maʿônîm</em>) appear in Ezra 2:50 as temple servants, suggesting they were eventually incorporated into the Judean community after military defeat. Uzziah's multi-front campaigns established Judah as the dominant regional power in the mid-8th century BCE.</p>",
        "8": "<p><strong>vayyittĕnû hāʿammônîm minḥāh leʿuzziyyāhû</strong> — 'The Ammonites gave tribute to Uzziah.' The Ammonites' tribute payment (<em>minḥāh</em> — the same word used for grain offerings, here a diplomatic gift/tax) signals Uzziah's regional supremacy. His reputation extended to Egypt (<em>ʿad-lĕḇôʾ mitsrāyim</em> — 'to the border of Egypt'), suggesting influence comparable to Solomon's sphere. The word <em>hayyiˈpheq</em> — 'he grew mighty' — from <em>ʾāmaẓ</em> (to be strong, courageous — H553) appears in v8; the contrast with v16 (<em>û bḥizqĕqāṯô gāḇah libbô</em> — 'when he was strong, his heart was lifted up') is the Chronicler's warning: strength without humility is the seedbed of pride and fall.</p>",
        "9": "<p><strong>vayyiḇen ʿuzziyyāhû miḡdālîm bîrûšālāim</strong> — 'Uzziah built towers in Jerusalem.' The defensive building program: towers at the Corner Gate (<em>šaʿar hapinnāh</em>), the Valley Gate (<em>šaʿar haggāy</em>), and the Angle (<em>hammiqṣôaʿ</em>) — key strategic points in Jerusalem's perimeter. These fortifications suggest Uzziah was responding to the city's vulnerability demonstrated by Jehoash's breach of the northern wall (25:23). The investment in Jerusalem's defenses signals the king's commitment to securing the capital, learning from his father's humiliation. Archaeological evidence of 8th-century BCE fortification expansion at Jerusalem's western hill may correlate with this Uzzian building program.</p>",
        "10": "<p><strong>vayyiḇen miḡdālîm bammiḏbār vayyaḥtsōḇ bōrôt rabbîm</strong> — 'He built towers in the wilderness and dug many cisterns.' The agricultural-military infrastructure: towers in the desert (<em>bammiḏbār</em>), cisterns (<em>bōrôt</em> — H877, hewn cisterns for water storage in the Negev), herds in the Shephelah and plains, farmers and vinedressers in the hill country and Carmel. <em>ʿuzziyyāhû ʾōhēḇ ʾadāmāh</em> — 'Uzziah was a lover of the soil.' This remarkable characterization paints a king who was not merely a warrior-politician but an agrarian visionary — understanding that military power rested on agricultural productivity. The water-storage infrastructure was critical for Negev settlement, enabling year-round occupation of otherwise seasonal terrain.</p>",
        "11": "<p><strong>vayhî leʿuzziyyāhû ḥayil ʿōśeh milḥāmāh</strong> — 'Uzziah had a force making war.' The military organization was systematic: <em>yōtsĕʾê tsāḇāʾ ligdûdîm bĕmispar peqûddātām beyad yĕʿîʾēl hasōfēr ûmaʿăśēyāhû haššōṭēr</em> — units organized by census count, under two officials (a scribe and an officer). The bureaucratic precision (<em>peqûddātām</em> — from <em>pāqaḏ</em>, to muster/count/visit) echoes Mosaic and Davidic military organization. The involvement of <em>ḥănanyāhû</em> (one of the king's commanders) under the overall command structure suggests a three-tier military hierarchy: king → commander → company-level officers (<em>sarei ʾāḇôt hakkōaḥ</em>).</p>",
        "12": "<p><strong>kōl mispar rāʾšê hāʾāḇôt legibborê ḥāyil</strong> — 'The total number of heads of ancestral houses of mighty warriors.' The census count: 2,600 heads of ancestral houses (<em>rāʾšê hāʾāḇôt</em>), commanding a force of 307,500 warriors (<em>ḥayil tsāḇāʾ</em> — a host of war). The numbers are comparable to Amaziah's force but with a clearer chain of command. The term <em>gibbōrê ḥāyil</em> (mighty warriors, men of valor) for the commanders preserves the Davidic military vocabulary. Under Uzziah this force operated on multiple fronts simultaneously — Philistines, Arabs, Ammonites — requiring logistical coordination far beyond what Israel had managed in the period of the judges.</p>",
        "13": "<p><strong>ûḇeyāḏām ḥêl tsāḇāʾ šĕlōš meʾôt ûšiḇʿat ʾălāfîm ûḥāmēš meʾôt</strong> — 'Under their command was a force of 307,500.' The combined fighting force under the 2,600 commanders: 307,500 men <em>ʿōśê milḥāmāh bĕkōaḥ ḥāyil</em> (making war with great power). This was the largest standing army in Judah's history according to the Chronicler — a reflection of Uzziah's 52-year reign allowing a full generational build-up. The round numbers suggest census data that has been summarized; actual regimental rosters likely contained far more granular information. The term <em>kōaḥ ḥāyil</em> (great power) frames the army as the expression of Uzziah's power — and sets up the irony that his greatest power led to his greatest sin.</p>",
        "14": "<p><strong>vayyākhen lāhem ʿuzziyyāhû lĕkhol-hatstsāḇāʾ</strong> — 'Uzziah provided for the entire army.' The standardized military equipment listed: <em>tsinnôt</em> (large body shields), <em>ḥănîtîm</em> (spears), <em>kôḇāʿîm</em> (helmets), <em>širyônôt</em> (scale armor), <em>qĕšātôt</em> (bows), and <em>ʾaḇnê qelaʿ</em> (sling-stones). The full kit for infantry (close combat and missile), including defensive armor, represents a professional army equipped at royal expense. The state-provisioning of military gear was unusual in the ancient Near East, where soldiers typically provided their own basic equipment; Uzziah's royal armory reflects his central administration and fiscal capacity.</p>",
        "15": "<p><strong>vayyaʿas bîrûšālāim ḥiššĕḇōnôt maḥăšeḇet ḥōšēḇ</strong> — 'He made in Jerusalem devices invented by skillful men.' The <em>ḥiššĕḇōnôt</em> (mechanical devices — H2810, from <em>ḥāšaḇ</em>, to devise/calculate) are often interpreted as war machines — catapults or ballistae for shooting arrows and hurling large stones. The phrase <em>maḥăšeḇet ḥōšēḇ</em> (an invention of an inventor/engineer) emphasizes their technological novelty. Archaeological evidence for stone-throwing war engines in the 8th century BCE Levant is limited but not impossible. The Chronicler's detail may reflect Assyrian-influenced military technology that Uzziah adopted — Tiglath-pileser III's campaigns introduced new siege and field artillery techniques into the region.</p>",
        "17": "<p><strong>vayyāḇôʾ ʾaḥaryāhû hakkōhēn veʿimmô ʾazaryāhû hakkōhēn</strong> — 'Azariah the priest went in after him, with 80 priests.' The confrontation: 80 priests (<em>šemōnîm kōhănîm bĕnê-ḥāyil</em> — 80 priests, men of valor) followed the high priest Azariah into the temple to confront the king. The phrase <em>bĕnê-ḥāyil</em> (men of valor) is usually applied to soldiers — its use for priests confronting a king marks the priestly intervention as requiring its own kind of courage. The priests stood against the most powerful king in Judah's recent history. Their collective action — eighty priests, not just one — protected the high priest from retaliation and demonstrated the priestly college's unanimity.</p>",
        "19": "<p><strong>vayyizzāʿep ʿuzziyyāhû ûbeyādô miqṭeret lezaqqēr</strong> — 'Uzziah was enraged; he had a censer in his hand to make incense.' The royal rage (<em>zāʿap</em> — H2196, to be indignant/wrathful) in response to priestly opposition triggered the divine judgment. As Uzziah raged before the priests, the <em>tsāraʿat</em> (leprosy — H6883, a skin disease rendering its bearer ritually impure and excluded from the community) broke out on his forehead. The symbolism is precise: the sin was offering incense at the altar of incense in the holy place — reserved for the anointed priests. The judgment appeared on his forehead — the most visible part of the body, at the location where the high priest wore his golden plate (<em>tsîts</em>) reading 'Holy to YHWH' (Exod 28:36-38). Uzziah's presumption on priestly territory was marked on his own flesh.</p>",
        "21": "<p><strong>vayhî ʿuzziyyāhû hammelekh metsōrāʿ ʿad-yôm mōtô</strong> — 'King Uzziah was leprous until the day of his death.' The double exclusion: <em>yāšaḇ-bêt haḥofšît metsōrāʿ</em> (he lived in an isolated house, being leprous) — the leper's required separation from society (Lev 13:46). His son Jotham governed the kingdom (<em>ʿal-bêt hammelekh šōfēṭ ʾet-ʿam hāʾārets</em>) as co-regent during Uzziah's illness. The duration — until his death — meant possibly decades of isolation. The phrase <em>bêt haḥofšît</em> (house of freedom/isolation) is a technical term for a leper colony or quarantine house. The king who reached for the highest priestly function ended excluded from the lowest requirements for communal life.</p>",
        "22": "<p><strong>weyeter diḇrê ʿuzziyyāhû hārīšonîm vehaʾăḥarōnîm kāṯaḇ yĕšaʿyāhû</strong> — 'The rest of the acts of Uzziah, first and last, Isaiah son of Amoz wrote.' The attribution of Uzziah's full biographical record to <em>yĕšaʿyāhû ben-ʾāmôts</em> (Isaiah son of Amoz) is unique in Chronicles — the only explicit citation of a writing prophet as historian. Isaiah's prophetic ministry began in 'the year King Uzziah died' (Isa 6:1) and spanned four reigns. His access to royal records as a court-connected prophet (he was reportedly of royal or noble lineage) would have made him an authoritative chronicler. The citation validates Chronicles' historical sources and connects the Uzziah narrative to the major prophetic corpus of the 8th century.</p>",
        "23": "<p><strong>vayyiškab ʿuzziyyāhû ʿim-ʾăḇōtāyw vayyiqqāḇĕrû ʾōtô ʿim-ʾăḇōtāyw</strong> — 'Uzziah slept with his fathers; they buried him with his fathers.' The burial note is diplomatically ambiguous: <em>bisdēh haqqeḇûrāh ʾăšer lammĕlākhîm</em> — 'in the burial field that belonged to the kings.' This may mean an adjacent field rather than the royal tombs themselves — the leprosy exclusion extending even to burial. Josephus (Ant. 9.10.4) records that Uzziah was buried in a royal garden near the royal cemetery. A first-century CE ossuary inscription found in Jerusalem reads 'Hither were brought the bones of Uzziah, king of Judah — do not open' — suggesting a secondary reburial, perhaps relocating his remains when his original tomb was moved.</p>",
    },
    "27": {
        "1": "<p><strong>ben-esrîm veḥāmēš šānāh yôtām bemalekô</strong> — 'Jotham was 25 years old when he became king.' <em>Yôtām</em> (H3147 — 'YHWH is perfect/complete') began his reign as the effective ruler during his father's leprosy (26:21) before formally succeeding him. His 16-year reign is marked by the Chronicler's most unequivocal positive evaluation: <em>vayyaʿas hayyāšār beʿênê YHWH kekōl ʾăšer-ʿāśāh ʾuzziyyāhû ʾāḇîhū</em> — 'he did what was right in YHWH's eyes, just as Uzziah his father had done.' But unlike Uzziah, Jotham's statement of approval is NOT followed by a fall. He is Judah's quiet righteous king, overshadowed by his more dramatic father and son.</p>",
        "3": "<p><strong>hûʾ bānāh ʾet-šaʿar bêt-YHWH hāʿelyôn</strong> — 'He built the upper gate of the house of YHWH.' The <em>šaʿar bêt-YHWH hāʿelyôn</em> (upper gate of the house of YHWH) was likely the northern gate of the temple mount, mentioned in 2 Kgs 15:35 and Jer 20:2. Jotham's building program combined temple renovation with city fortification: walls on the Ophel hill (<em>ḥômat hāʿōpel</em> — the southern spur of the temple mount) and cities in the Judean highlands (<em>ʿārîm bahărar yehûdāh</em>). The forest fortifications (<em>ûḇayĕʿārôt bānnāh ḇîrāniyyôt ûmigdālîm</em>) suggest a defensive posture toward Ephraim. Jotham's building investments secured Judah's infrastructure during a period of external pressure.</p>",
        "4": "<p><strong>ûʿārîm bānāh behărar yehûdāh ûḇāḥarāšîm bīrāniyyôt ûmigdālîm</strong> — 'He built cities in the Judean highlands and in the forests, fortresses and towers.' The three-part construction program — cities, forts (<em>bîrāniyyôt</em> — H1003, fortresses/citadels), towers (<em>migdālîm</em>) — established a defensive network throughout the hill country. This infrastructure would prove critical when Rezin of Aram and Pekah of Israel threatened Judah during the Syro-Ephraimite crisis (Isa 7; 2 Kgs 16). Jotham's military-civilian investment strengthened Judah precisely for the storms that would break in his son Ahaz's time. The Chronicler implicitly credits Jotham's foresight with giving Judah the infrastructure that Ahaz would subsequently squander.</p>",
        "5": "<p><strong>hûʾ nilaḥam ʿim-melek benê-ʿammôn vayyikhbĕšēm</strong> — 'He fought against the king of the Ammonites and subdued them.' The Ammonite campaign yielded tribute for three consecutive years: <em>meʾāh kikkar kesep ʿăśeret ʾălāfîm kōr ḥittîm veʿăśeret ʾălāfîm śĕʿōrîm</em> (100 talents of silver, 10,000 cors of wheat, 10,000 cors of barley). These annual payments (year one, two, three) established Jotham's regional authority east of the Jordan. The Ammonites appear in the region from Deut 2 onward; their subjugation by Jotham continues the pattern established by Uzziah (26:8). The three-year tribute period suggests a treaty arrangement that outlasted any single military campaign.</p>",
        "7": "<p><strong>weyeter diḇrê yôtām wekhol-milḥāmōtāyw ûdĕrākhāyw</strong> — 'The rest of the acts of Jotham, all his wars and his ways.' The source reference: <em>hinnām ketûḇîm ʿal-sefer malkhê yisrāʾel wîhûdāh</em> (written in the Book of the Kings of Israel and Judah). The Chronicler commends Jotham in his closing formula: <em>vayyitḥazzēq yôtām kî hēkhîn drākhāyw lifnê YHWH ʾĕlōhāyw</em> — 'Jotham grew mighty, because he made his ways straight before YHWH his God.' The phrase <em>hēkhîn drākhāyw</em> (established/directed his ways) is a Chronicler's idiom for covenant faithfulness — a king who ordered his life according to YHWH's covenant requirements. The note that the people still acted corruptly (<em>hāʿām ʿôd mĕšaḥătîm</em>) marks the gap between the righteous king and his less-than-righteous subjects.</p>",
        "8": "<p><strong>ben-esrîm veḥāmēš šānāh hāyāh bemalekô ûšĕš ʿeśrēh šānāh mālaḵ bîrûšālāim</strong> — 'He was 25 years old when he became king and reigned 16 years in Jerusalem.' The brief summary emphasizes Jotham's straightforward, uncomplicated reign — no prophets rebuke him, no idolatry mars his record, no military disaster humiliates him. In the Chronicler's pantheon of Judean kings, Jotham is the quiet achiever: not as spectacular as Solomon, not as reforming as Hezekiah or Josiah, but consistently righteous throughout. His reign provides breathing space between the mixed legacies of Uzziah and Ahaz — a single-chapter interlude of genuine covenant faithfulness.</p>",
        "9": "<p><strong>vayyiškab yôtām ʿim-ʾăḇōtāyw vayyiqqāḇĕrû ʾōtô beʿîr dāwîd</strong> — 'Jotham slept with his fathers and they buried him in the City of David.' The honorable burial in the City of David — the royal necropolis — reflects his unclouded reign. Unlike Amaziah (buried in a field near the royal tombs) or Uzziah (buried in a separate royal garden), Jotham received the standard burial of a faithful Davidic king. The succession formula — <em>vayyimlōkh ʾāḥāz bĕnô taḥtāyw</em> (his son Ahaz reigned in his place) — opens the door to the darkest chapter in 8th-century Judah. The stark contrast between the father's righteousness and the son's apostasy is the Chronicler's sharpest dynastic irony.</p>",
    },
    "28": {
        "1": "<p><strong>ben-esrîm šānāh ʾāḥāz bemalekô</strong> — 'Ahaz was 20 years old when he became king.' <em>ʾĀḥāz</em> (H271 — 'he has grasped/held') begins the most theologically dark reign since Rehoboam's division of the kingdom. The immediate contrast with his father: <em>welōʾ-ʿāśāh hayyāšār beʿênê YHWH kelāwîd ʾāḇîhū</em> — 'he did not do what was right in YHWH's eyes like David his father.' The David comparison (rare in Chronicles) signals the magnitude of the departure: Ahaz did not merely fail to match Jotham's righteousness; he broke the fundamental Davidic covenant standard. The Chronicler will detail precisely how total this departure was.</p>",
        "2": "<p><strong>vayyēlek bidarkê malkhê yisrāʾel</strong> — 'He walked in the ways of the kings of Israel.' The ultimate condemnation in the Chronicler's framework: walking in the ways of the northern kings — the dynasty of Jeroboam's golden calves and Ahab's Baal worship. The specific abomination: <em>gam massêkhôt ʿāśāh labbaʿālîm</em> (he even made cast idols for the Baals). The plural <em>bĕʿālîm</em> (Baals — the Canaanite storm-deity in regional manifestations) indicates systematic polytheism, not a single act. Ahaz was the first Judean king to explicitly introduce the Baal cult at the state level — worse than the northern kingdom's calves (which were meant to represent YHWH), Baal worship was full-scale paganism.</p>",
        "4": "<p><strong>vayzabbeaḥ vayĕqaṭṭēr babbāmôt ʿal-haggeḇāʿôt</strong> — 'He sacrificed and burned incense on the high places, hills, and under every green tree.' The phrase <em>taḥat kol-ʿēts raʿănān</em> (under every green/leafy tree) is the standard Deuteronomic formula for Canaanite nature worship (Deut 12:2; 2 Kgs 16:4; Jer 2:20). The high places (<em>bāmôt</em>), hills (<em>gĕḇāʿôt</em>), and sacred trees formed the decentralized worship network of Canaanite religion. Ahaz did not merely tolerate these sites — he actively participated in worship at them. The Chronicler's accumulation of locations emphasizes the comprehensiveness of Ahaz's apostasy: everywhere in the land, Baal was being worshiped with royal patronage.</p>",
        "5": "<p><strong>vayyittenēhû YHWH ʾĕlōhāyw beyad melek ʾărām</strong> — 'YHWH his God gave him into the hand of the king of Aram.' The first military judgment: Aram (Damascus under Rezin) defeated Judah and deported a great number (<em>šĕḇî gādôl vayyāḇēʾ dammāśeq</em> — a great captivity he brought to Damascus). The second judgment: <em>veḡam beyad melek-yisrāʾel nitten</em> (also given into the hand of the king of Israel). Pekah son of Remaliah killed 120,000 Judean warriors (<em>gibbôrê ḥāyil</em>) in one day — a catastrophic defeat. The Chronicler's explanation is explicit: <em>baʿăzûḇām ʾet-YHWH ʾĕlōhê ʾăḇōtêhem</em> — 'because they had abandoned YHWH, the God of their fathers.' The causal chain — apostasy → military defeat — operates with the precision of covenant law.</p>",
        "6": "<p><strong>vayyahărōg pĕqaḥ ben-rĕmályāhû bîhûdāh meʾāh veʿeśrîm ʾelep</strong> — '120,000 killed in Judah by Pekah son of Remaliah.' The slaughter included <em>Maʿăśēyāhû ben-hammelekh</em> (Maaseiah the king's son), <em>ʿAzrîqām nāgîd habbāyit</em> (Azrikam the chief of the palace), and <em>ʾElqānāh hammiśneh lammeleḵ</em> (Elkanah, second to the king). The specific naming of these three officials alongside the 120,000 shows the thoroughness of the disaster: the royal family, the palace administration, and the army were simultaneously devastated. This is the worst single-battle defeat in Judah's history. The three named victims represent court, palace, and military — a comprehensive institutional collapse.</p>",
        "7": "<p><strong>vayyišbû benê-yisrāʾel meʾăḥêhem meʾātayim ʾelef</strong> — 'The sons of Israel captured 200,000 of their brothers.' The captivity: 200,000 Judean prisoners (<em>ʿăḥêhem</em> — 'their brothers,' emphasizing the fratricidal nature of the war) taken to Samaria, plus plunder. The double crisis — enormous battle casualties and mass deportation of the civilian population — threatened Judah's survival as a functioning society. The Chronicler is setting the stage for the remarkable prophetic intervention in vv9-15: the prophet Oded who would use covenant fraternity (<em>ʾăḥêhem</em>) to persuade the Israelite army to release the captives.</p>",
        "8": "<p><strong>vayyiqqāḥû šĕḇî meʾăḥêhem šemōnîm ûmāʾtayim ʾelef</strong> — 'They took 200,000 captives from their brothers.' The captives were transported toward Samaria with large amounts of plunder (<em>bizzāh rabbāh</em>). The Hebrew term <em>ʾăḥêhem</em> (their brothers — all Israelites, north and south, shared the Abrahamic covenant) is key: the northern kingdom was treating covenantal brothers as war-slaves. This violated the covenant terms that governed how Israelites were to treat enslaved compatriots (Exod 21:1-11; Lev 25:39-46). The prophetic intervention was not mere humanitarian sentiment but a specific application of the covenant law on the enslavement of fellow Israelites.</p>",
        "10": "<p><strong>veʿattāh likhbōš liḇnê-yehûdāh wîrûšālāim ʾattem ʾōmĕrîm laʿăḇādîm</strong> — 'Now you intend to subjugate Judah and Jerusalem as male and female slaves.' The prophet Oded's argument: Israel was about to make permanent slaves of Judeans — reducing covenant brothers to chattel. The word <em>ʿăḇādîm veišfāḥôt</em> (male and female slaves) is the technical vocabulary for slave status. Oded's rhetorical question: <em>hălōʾ raq ʾattem ʿimmakem ʾăšāmôt laYHWH ʾĕlōhêkem</em> — 'Do you not also have guilts before YHWH your God?' Israel was itself under YHWH's judgment — an enslaving people were themselves covenant-breakers without standing to enslave others. The ethical argument is also strategic: YHWH's wrath would fall on Israel too.</p>",
        "11": "<p><strong>veʿattāh šimʿûnî vehaśîḇû haššĕḇî ʾăšer šĕḇîtem meʾăḥêkem</strong> — 'Now hear me, and send back the captives you took from your brothers.' Oded's command is direct (<em>haśîḇû</em> — return, send back — the root <em>šûḇ</em> of repentance applied to a concrete act). The warning: <em>kî ḥărôn ʾap-YHWH ʿălêkem</em> — 'for YHWH's fierce anger is upon you.' The language of <em>ḥărôn ʾap</em> (burning anger) is the Deuteronomic warning for covenant breach (Deut 11:17; 29:27). This is one of the most dramatic prophetic interventions in Chronicles: a single prophet before a victorious army demanding the release of 200,000 prisoners — and being obeyed.</p>",
        "12": "<p><strong>vayyāqumû ʾănāšîm merrāʾšê benê-ʾeprayim ʿăzaryāhû ben-yĕhôḥānān</strong> — 'Certain heads of the sons of Ephraim stood up.' Four named leaders of the Ephraimite tribe confronted the returning army: <em>ʿAzaryāhû ben-yĕhôḥānān, berkheyāhû ben-mĕšillēmôt, yĕḥizqiyyāhû ben-šallûm, ʿAmāśā ben-ḥadlāy</em>. Their intervention against the army was politically risky — they opposed their own king's apparent intent to profit from the captives. The naming of four specific leaders validates this as a historical record: these were real individuals who took a stand. The Chronicler's purpose: to show that even within the apostate north, YHWH could raise up voices of covenant conscience.</p>",
        "13": "<p><strong>wayyōmĕrû lāhem lōʾ-tāḇîʾû ʾet-haššĕḇî hēnnāh</strong> — 'They said to them, Do not bring the captives here.' The Ephraimite leaders argued: <em>kî leʾašmah ʾal-YHWH ʿālênû ʾattem ōmĕrîm lahasîf ʿal-ḥaṭṭōʾtênû weʿal-ʾašmātênû</em> — 'for you intend to add to our sins and guilt before YHWH.' The word <em>ʾašmāh</em> (H819 — guilt, guilt-offering, trespass) appears twice — an unusual theological vocabulary acknowledging Israel's own accumulated covenant violations. The leaders saw that adding enslavement of brothers to the existing guilt would bring YHWH's judgment on Israel itself. Their theological reasoning was sounder than their king's: covenantal responsibility for kin overrode military right to spoil.</p>",
        "14": "<p><strong>vayyaʿăzōḇ heḥālûts ʾet-haššĕḇî veʾet-habbizzāh lifnê hasarîm</strong> — 'The armed men left the captives and the plunder before the officials.' The compliance was total — the army released both the prisoners and the war-spoil to the Ephraimite leaders who had confronted them. The transaction was communal: the four named leaders (<em>vayyāqumû hāʾănāšîm ʾăšer-niqqĕḇû ḇĕšēmôt</em> — the men designated by name) organized the relief operation. The word <em>leḇûšâ</em> (clothing) — the stripped captives needed to be re-clothed. The relief effort covered basics: clothes, sandals, food, drink, oil (for wounds and anointing), and transportation (<em>ḥămôrîm</em> — donkeys for the weak).</p>",
        "16": "<p><strong>bāʿēt hahîʾ šālaḥ hammelekh ʾāḥāz ʿal-malkhê ʾaššûr laʿăzôr-lô</strong> — 'At that time King Ahaz sent to the kings of Assyria for help.' Ahaz's response to the military crisis was the opposite of Asa (14:11), Jehoshaphat (18:31), and Hezekiah (32:20) — instead of seeking YHWH, he sought Assyria. <em>ʾAššûr</em> under Tiglath-pileser III was the rising superpower of the era; Ahaz's appeal represented a fundamental foreign-policy shift that would have generational consequences. The Chronicler's note that Ahaz sent to the <em>malkhê ʾaššûr</em> (kings of Assyria, plural — possibly referring to Tiglath-pileser's throne name and vassal kings) distinguishes this appeal as a treaty relationship, not a one-time military request.</p>",
        "17": "<p><strong>veʿôd ʾedôm bāʾû vayyakkû bîhûdāh vayyišbû šĕḇî</strong> — 'Also the Edomites came and attacked Judah and took captives.' The multiple simultaneous attacks: Edom raided and deported Judeans; the Philistines (<em>pĕlishtîm</em>) raided the cities of the Shephelah and Negev, occupying <em>bêt-šemeš, ʾayyālôn, gĕḏērôt, śokhô ûḇimôṯāyw, tîmnāh ûḇimôṯāyw, gimzô ûḇimôṯāyw</em> — seven named cities with their surrounding villages. These were precisely the territories Uzziah had captured and fortified (26:6) — Ahaz's apostasy reversed two generations of Judean territorial gain. The Edomite captives are an ironic reversal of Amaziah's atrocities at Sela (25:12): the people Judah had thrown off cliffs were now taking Judean prisoners.</p>",
        "18": "<p><strong>vayyišlĕḥû pĕlishtîm baʿārê haššĕpēlāh ûhannegev lîhûdāh</strong> — 'The Philistines raided the cities of the Shephelah and the Negev of Judah.' The specific city list — Bethshemesh, Aijalon, Gederoth, Soco, Timnah, Gimzo — were strategically important Shephelah towns. Aijalon and Bethshemesh were ancient Danite/Judean border cities mentioned in the tribal allotments (Josh 15, 19). Their loss opened the western approaches to Jerusalem. Timnah was the site of Samson's marriage (Judg 14), Gimzo a border marker. The comprehensiveness of the loss — every named town and its dependent villages — shows the collapse of Uzziah's western defensive network within a single generation of apostasy.</p>",
        "19": "<p><strong>kî-hikhnaʿ YHWH ʾet-yehûdāh baʿăḇûr ʾāḥāz melek-yisrāʾel</strong> — 'Because YHWH humbled Judah on account of Ahaz king of Israel.' The theological explanation: <em>hikhnaʿ</em> (H3665 — to humble, bring low, subdue) is a key Chronicler's term for YHWH's disciplinary action. The remarkable phrase <em>ʾāḥāz melek-yisrāʾel</em> (Ahaz king of Israel) — calling a Judean king by the northern kingdom's title — is deliberate: Ahaz had so thoroughly adopted Israelite apostasy that he deserved the title of the apostate north. The explanation <em>kî hiphrîaʿ pĕrûʿôt bîhûdāh ûmaʿal maʿal baYHWH</em> (for he had caused disorder in Judah and was deeply unfaithful to YHWH) gives the dual charge: social chaos and covenant infidelity.</p>",
        "20": "<p><strong>vayyāḇōʾ ʿālāyw tiglat pilʾeser melek ʾaššûr vayyātsar lô welōʾ ḥizzĕqô</strong> — 'Tiglath-pileser king of Assyria came to him and distressed him rather than strengthening him.' The Assyrian help Ahaz purchased was a catastrophic miscalculation: <em>welōʾ ḥizzĕqô</em> (did not strengthen him). Tiglath-pileser III (745-727 BCE) was a transformative Assyrian emperor who reorganized the empire, deported conquered peoples, and created provincial structures. Ahaz's tribute bought temporary relief from Aram and Israel while making Judah an Assyrian client state. The word <em>vayyātsār lô</em> (he distressed him) is the ironic reversal: the king called for help and received oppression. The Chronicler's verdict: Ahaz's political gamble failed on its own terms.</p>",
        "21": "<p><strong>vayyāḥālōm ʾāḥāz ʾet-bêt-YHWH veʾet-bêt hammelekh veʾet-hasarîm</strong> — 'Ahaz stripped the house of YHWH, the palace, and the officials.' The desperate tribute payment to Tiglath-pileser involved looting three sources: <em>bêt-YHWH</em> (the temple treasury), <em>bêt hammelekh</em> (the palace), and <em>hasarîm</em> (the nobles' wealth — presumably forced contributions). The word <em>vayyāḥălēq</em> (divided up, distributed — H2505) suggests systematic distribution of collected wealth as tribute. This was the second stripping of the temple treasury in the Chronicler's narrative (after Jehoash in 25:24) — each time caused by the king's apostasy. The Chronicler's comment: <em>welōʾ laʿezrāh lô</em> (but it did not help him) completes the triple failure of the Assyrian alliance.</p>",
        "23": "<p><strong>vayyizbaḥ laʾĕlōhê dammāśeq hammakkîm ʾōtô</strong> — 'He sacrificed to the gods of Damascus that had struck him.' The theological logic Ahaz used: <em>kî ʾĕlōhê malkhê ʾărām hēm maʿăzĕrîm ʾōtām lahēm ʾezabbēaḥ vaʿăzārûnî</em> — 'the gods of the kings of Aram help them; I will sacrifice to them so they will help me.' This was the ANE logic of henotheism: each nation's god had effective power in his territory. But the Chronicler has already shown (25:14) the absurdity of worshiping the gods of a conquered nation. The Damascene gods had not saved Damascus from Tiglath-pileser (who captured Damascus in 732 BCE — 2 Kgs 16:9). Ahaz worshiped gods that had demonstrably failed their own people, seeking help that their own devotees had not received.</p>",
        "24": "<p><strong>vayyeʾesōp ʾāḥāz ʾet-kĕlê bêt-hāʾĕlōhîm vayyĕqattsēts</strong> — 'Ahaz gathered the vessels of the house of God and cut them in pieces.' The systematic desecration of the temple: sacred vessels (<em>kĕlê bêt-hāʾĕlōhîm</em>) were cut up (<em>vayyĕqattsēts</em> — H7112, to cut in pieces), the temple doors were shut (<em>vayyisgōr ʾet-daltôt bêt-YHWH</em>), and altars were set up at every corner in Jerusalem (<em>bĕkhol-pinnāh bîrûšālāim</em>). The closing of the temple — unprecedented in Judah's history — was the ultimate apostasy: the Davidic king locked the house of YHWH. The altars at every city corner indicate comprehensive restructuring of Judah's worship from YHWH-centered to polytheistic. The <em>miqṭārôt</em> (incense altars) in every Judean city (v25) completed the nation's apostasy.</p>",
        "25": "<p><strong>ûḇĕkhol-ʿîr vaʿîr bîhûdāh ʿāśāh bāmôt leqaṭṭēr lēʾlōhîm ʾăḥērîm</strong> — 'In every city in Judah he made high places to burn incense to other gods.' The phrase <em>bĕkhol-ʿîr vaʿîr</em> (in every city and city — an emphatic distributive) with <em>ʾĕlōhîm ʾăḥērîm</em> (other gods) invokes the First Commandment's specific prohibition (Exod 20:3). Ahaz's systematic program represented the official disestablishment of YHWH worship throughout the kingdom. The Chronicler's verdict: <em>vayyakʿēs ʾet-YHWH ʾĕlōhê ʾăḇōtāyw</em> — 'he provoked YHWH, the God of his fathers, to anger.' The word <em>kaʿas</em> (H3707 — to vex, provoke, be angry) is the covenantal term for Israel's chronic offense against YHWH (Deut 32:21; 1 Kgs 14:9,22). Ahaz's reign is the nadir before Hezekiah's reform.</p>",
        "26": "<p><strong>weyeter diḇrāyw ûkhol-drākhāyw hārīšonîm vehaʾăḥarōnîm</strong> — 'The rest of his acts and all his ways, first and last.' The source reference: <em>hinnām ketûḇîm ʿal-sefer malkhê yehûdāh veyisrāʾel</em> (written in the Book of the Kings of Judah and Israel). The Chronicler's closing formula is notably brief for Ahaz — no eulogy, no positive final note. The source citation functions as a way of directing readers to fuller accounts while the Chronicler himself has said enough. Ahaz's 16 years were characterized by systematic dismantling of everything the Davidic covenant stood for — and the source chronicles would tell the full, even darker story.</p>",
        "27": "<p><strong>vayyiškab ʾāḥāz ʿim-ʾăḇōtāyw vayyiqbĕrûhû beʿîr bîrûšālāim</strong> — 'Ahaz slept with his fathers and they buried him in the city, in Jerusalem.' The burial notice for Ahaz is pointed in its omission: <em>welōʾ hĕḇîʾuhû lĕqiḇrôt malkhê yisrāʾel</em> — 'they did not bring him to the tombs of the kings of Israel.' Buried in the city but not in the royal tombs — a posthumous verdict on his unfaithfulness. The Davidic line required royal burial with the ancestors; exclusion from the royal tombs was a form of posthumous judgment (cf. Jehoram in 21:20, who also was excluded). The succession to Hezekiah immediately follows — and the contrast could not be sharper. The Chronicler positions this exclusion as the bridge to the great reform that would begin in the very next verse.</p>",
    }
}

def merge_comm(existing, new_data):
    # INTENT: Merge new commentary entries without overwriting existing ones — safe to re-run
    for ch, verses in new_data.items():
        if ch not in existing:
            existing[ch] = {}
        for v, html in verses.items():
            if v not in existing[ch]:
                existing[ch][v] = html

out_path = pathlib.Path("data/commentary/mkt-original/2chronicles.json")
existing = json.loads(out_path.read_text()) if out_path.exists() else {}
before = sum(len(existing.get(c, {})) for c in DATA)
merge_comm(existing, DATA)
after = sum(len(existing.get(c, {})) for c in DATA)
out_path.write_text(json.dumps(existing, ensure_ascii=False, indent=2))
print(f"  wrote {out_path}")
print(f"2chronicles mkt-original: added up to {after - before} verses across ch25-28")
